# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ragdoll-physics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] In computational chemistry, a **constraint algorithm** is a method for satisfying the Newtonian motion of a rigid body which consists of mass points.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] A restraint algorithm is used to ensure that the distance between mass points is maintained.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] The general steps involved are: (i) choose novel unconstrained coordinates (internal coordinates), (ii) introduce explicit constraint forces, (iii) minimize constraint forces implicitly by the technique of Lagrange multipliers or projection methods.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] Constraint algorithms are often applied to molecular dynamics simulations.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] Although such simulations are sometimes performed using internal coordinates that automatically satisfy the bond-length, bond-angle and torsion-angle constraints, simulations may also be performed using explicit or implicit constraint forces for these three constraints.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] However, explicit constraint forces give rise to inefficiency; more computational power is required to get a trajectory of a given length.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] Therefore, internal coordinates and implicit-force constraint solvers are generally preferred.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] Constraint algorithms achieve computational efficiency by neglecting motion along some degrees of freedom.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] For instance, in atomistic molecular dynamics, typically the length of covalent bonds to hydrogen are constrained; however, constraint algorithms should not be used if vibrations along these degrees of freedom are important for the phenomenon being studied.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] where **M** is a *mass matrix* and **q** is the vector of generalized coordinates that describe the particles' positions.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] For example, the vector **q** may be a *3N* Cartesian coordinates of the particle positions **r***k*, where *k* runs from 1 to *N*; in the absence of constraints, **M** would be the *3N*x*3N* diagonal square matrix of the particle masses.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] The vector **f** represents the generalized forces and the scalar *V*(**q**) represents the potential energy, both of which are functions of the generalized coordinates **q**.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] For brevity, these functions *g**i* are grouped into an *M*-dimensional vector **g** below.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] The task is to solve the combined set of differential-algebraic (DAE) equations, instead of just the ordinary differential equations (ODE) of Newton's second law.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] This problem was studied in detail by Joseph Louis Lagrange, who laid out most of the methods for solving it.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] The simplest approach is to define new generalized coordinates that are unconstrained; this approach eliminates the algebraic equations and reduces the problem once again to solving an ordinary differential equation.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] The drawback of this approach is that the equations may become unwieldy and complex; for example, the mass matrix **M** may become non-diagonal and depend on the generalized coordinates.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] A second approach is to introduce explicit forces that work to maintain the constraint; for example, one could introduce strong spring forces that enforce the distances among mass points within a "rigid" body.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] The two difficulties of this approach are that the constraints are not satisfied exactly, and the strong forces may require very short time-steps, making simulations inefficient computationally.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] A third approach is to use a method such as Lagrange multipliers or projection to the constraint manifold to determine the coordinate adjustments necessary to satisfy the constraints.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] Finally, there are various hybrid approaches in which different sets of constraints are satisfied by different methods, e.g., internal coordinates, explicit forces and implicit-force solutions.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] The simplest approach to satisfying constraints in energy minimization and molecular dynamics is to represent the mechanical system in so-called *internal coordinates* corresponding to unconstrained independent degrees of freedom of the system.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] For example, the dihedral angles of a protein are an independent set of coordinates that specify the positions of all the atoms without requiring any constraints.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] The difficulty of such internal-coordinate approaches is twofold: the Newtonian equations of motion become much more complex and the internal coordinates may be difficult to define for cyclic systems of constraints, e.g., in ring puckering or when a protein has a disulfide bond.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] The original methods for efficient recursive energy minimization in internal coordinates were developed by Gō and coworkers.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] Efficient recursive, internal-coordinate constraint solvers were extended to molecular dynamics.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] Analogous methods were applied later to other systems.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] In most of molecular dynamics simulations that use constraint algorithms, constraints are enforced using the method of Lagrange multipliers.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] where $\scriptstyle \mathbf {x} _{k\alpha }(t)$ and $\scriptstyle \mathbf {x} _{k\beta }(t)$ are the positions of the two particles involved in the *k*th constraint at the time *t* and $d_{k}$ is the prescribed inter-particle distance.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] Adding the constraint forces does not change the total energy, as the net work done by the constraint forces (taken over the set of particles that the constraints act on) is zero.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] Note that the sign on $\lambda _{k}$ is arbitrary and some references have an opposite sign.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] where ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{i}(t+\Delta t)$ is the unconstrained (or uncorrected) position of the *i*th particle after integrating the unconstrained equations of motion.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] simultaneously for the n unknown Lagrange multipliers $\lambda _{k}$ .
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] Since not all particles contribute to all of constraints, $\mathbf {J} _{\sigma }$ is a block matrix and can be solved individually to block-unit of the matrix.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] In other words, $\mathbf {J} _{\sigma }$ can be solved individually for each molecule.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] Instead of constantly updating the vector ${\underline {\lambda }}$ , the iteration can be started with ${\underline {\lambda }}^{(0)}=\mathbf {0}$ , resulting in simpler expressions for $\sigma _{k}(t)$ and ${\frac {\partial \sigma _{k}(t)}{\partial \lambda _{j}}}$ .
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] The above procedure is repeated until the solution of constraint equations, $\sigma _{k}(t+\Delta t)$ , converges to a prescribed tolerance of a numerical error.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] Although there are a number of algorithms to compute the Lagrange multipliers, these difference is rely only on the methods to solve the system of equations.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] For this methods, quasi-Newton methods are commonly used.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] The SETTLE algorithm solves the system of non-linear equations analytically for $n=3$ constraints in constant time.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] Although it does not scale to larger numbers of constraints, it is very often used to constrain rigid water molecules, which are present in almost all biological simulations and are usually modelled using three constraints (e.g.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] The SHAKE algorithm was first developed for satisfying a bond geometry constraint during molecular dynamics simulations.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] The method was then generalised to handle any holonomic constraint, such as those required to maintain constant bond angles, or molecular rigidity.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] This amounts to assuming that $\mathbf {J} _{\sigma }$ is diagonally dominant and solving the k th equation only for the k unknown.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] for all $k=1\ldots n$ iteratively until the constraint equations $\sigma _{k}(t+\Delta t)$ are solved to a given tolerance.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] The calculation cost of each iteration is ${\mathcal {O}}(n)$ , and the iterations themselves converge linearly.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] A noniterative form of SHAKE was developed later on.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] Several variants of the SHAKE algorithm exist.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] Although they differ in how they compute or apply the constraints themselves, the constraints are still modelled using Lagrange multipliers which are computed using the Gauss–Seidel method.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] The original SHAKE algorithm is capable of constraining both rigid and flexible molecules (e.g. water, benzene and biphenyl) and introduces negligible error or energy drift into a molecular dynamics simulation.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] One issue with SHAKE is that the number of iterations required to reach a certain level of convergence does rise as molecular geometry becomes more complex.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] To reach 64 bit computer accuracy (a relative tolerance of $\approx 10^{-16}$ ) in a typical molecular dynamics simulation at a temperature of 310K, a 3-site water model having 3 constraints to maintain molecular geometry requires an average of 9 iterations (which is 3 per site per time-step).
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] A 4-site butane model with 5 constraints needs 17 iterations (22 per site), a 6-site benzene model with 12 constraints needs 36 iterations (72 per site), while a 12-site biphenyl model with 29 constraints requires 92 iterations (229 per site per time-step).
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] Hence the CPU requirements of the SHAKE algorithm can become significant, particularly if a molecular model has a high degree of rigidity.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] A later extension of the method, QSHAKE (Quaternion SHAKE) was developed as a faster alternative for molecules composed of rigid units, but it is not as general purpose.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] It works satisfactorily for *rigid* loops such as aromatic ring systems but QSHAKE fails for flexible loops, such as when a protein has a disulfide bond.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] Further extensions include RATTLE, WIGGLE, and MSHAKE.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] While RATTLE works the same way as SHAKE, yet using the Velocity Verlet time integration scheme, WIGGLE extends SHAKE and RATTLE by using an initial estimate for the Lagrange multipliers $\lambda _{k}$ based on the particle velocities.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] It is worth mentioning that MSHAKE computes corrections on the constraint *forces*, achieving better convergence.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] A final modification to the SHAKE algorithm is the P-SHAKE algorithm that is applied to very rigid or semi-rigid molecules.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] P-SHAKE computes and updates a pre-conditioner which is applied to the constraint gradients before the SHAKE iteration, causing the Jacobian $\mathbf {J} _{\sigma }$ to become diagonal or strongly diagonally dominant.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] The thus de-coupled constraints converge much faster (quadratically as opposed to linearly) at a cost of ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{2})$ .
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] The M-SHAKE algorithm solves the non-linear system of equations using Newton's method directly.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] is solved exactly using an LU decomposition.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] Each iteration costs ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{3})$ operations, yet the solution converges quadratically, requiring fewer iterations than SHAKE.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] This solution was first proposed in 1986 by Ciccotti and Ryckaert under the title "the matrix method", yet differed in the solution of the linear system of equations.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] Ciccotti and Ryckaert suggest inverting the matrix $\mathbf {J} _{\sigma }$ directly, yet doing so only once, in the first iteration.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] The first iteration then costs ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{3})$ operations, whereas the following iterations cost only ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{2})$ operations (for the matrix-vector multiplication).
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] This improvement comes at a cost though, since the Jacobian is no longer updated, convergence is only linear, albeit at a much faster rate than for the SHAKE algorithm.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] Several variants of this approach based on sparse matrix techniques were studied by Barth *et al.*.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] The SHAPE algorithm is a multicenter analog of SHAKE for constraining rigid bodies of three or more centers.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] This approach involves a single 3×3 matrix diagonalization followed by three or four rapid Newton iterations to determine the rotation matrix.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] SHAPE provides the identical trajectory that is provided with fully converged iterative SHAKE, yet it is found to be more efficient and more accurate than SHAKE when applied to systems involving three or more centers.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] It extends the ability of SHAKE like constraints to linear systems with three or more atoms, planar systems with four or more atoms, and to significantly larger rigid structures where SHAKE is intractable.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] It also allows rigid bodies to be linked with one or two common centers (e.g. peptide planes) by solving rigid body constraints iteratively in the same basic manner that SHAKE is used for atoms involving more than one SHAKE constraint.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] An alternative constraint method, LINCS (Linear Constraint Solver) was developed in 1997 by Hess, Bekker, Berendsen and Fraaije, and was based on the 1986 method of Edberg, Evans and Morriss (EEM), and a modification thereof by Baranyai and Evans (BE).
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] This approximation only works for matrices with eigenvalues smaller than 1, making the LINCS algorithm suitable only for molecules with low connectivity.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] LINCS has been reported to be 3–4 times faster than SHAKE.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] Hybrid methods have also been introduced in which the constraints are divided into two groups; the constraints of the first group are solved using internal coordinates whereas those of the second group are solved using constraint forces, e.g., by a Lagrange multiplier or projection method.
[src:ragdoll-physics/constraint-computational-chemistry] This approach was pioneered by Lagrange, and result in *Lagrange equations of the mixed type*.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] IK operations are computationally much more complex than forward kinematics, in which joint parameters are trigonometrically calculated to achieve the position and orientation of the chain's end.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] In robotics, inverse kinematics makes use of the kinematics equations to determine the joint parameters that provide a desired configuration (position and rotation) for each of the robot's end effectors.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] This is important because robot tasks are performed with the end effectors, while control effort applies to the joints.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] Determining the movement of a robot so that its end effectors move from an initial configuration to a desired configuration is known as motion planning.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] Inverse kinematics transforms the motion plan into joint actuator trajectories for the robot.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] Similar formulas determine the positions of the skeleton of an animated character that is to move in a particular way in a film, or of a vehicle such as a car or boat containing the camera which is shooting a scene of a film.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] The movement of a kinematic chain, whether it is a robot or an animated character, is modeled by the kinematics equations of the chain.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] These equations define the configuration of the chain in terms of its joint parameters.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] Forward kinematics uses the joint parameters to compute the configuration of the chain, and inverse kinematics reverses this calculation to determine the joint parameters that achieve a desired configuration.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] Kinematic analysis is one of the first steps in the design of most industrial robots.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] Kinematic analysis allows the designer to obtain information on the position of each component within the mechanical system.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] This information is necessary for subsequent dynamic analysis along with control paths.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] Inverse kinematics is an example of the kinematic analysis of a constrained system of rigid bodies, or kinematic chain.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] The kinematic equations of a robot can be used to define the loop equations of a complex articulated system.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] These loop equations are nonlinear constraints on the configuration parameters of the system.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] The independent parameters in these equations are known as the degrees of freedom of the system.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] While analytical solutions to the inverse kinematics problem exist for a wide range of kinematic chains, computer modeling and animation tools often use Newton's method to solve the nonlinear kinematics equations.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] When trying to find an analytical solution it is often convenient to exploit the geometry of the system and decompose it using subproblems with known solutions.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] Other applications of inverse kinematic algorithms include interactive manipulation, animation control and collision avoidance.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] Inverse kinematics is important to game programming and 3D animation, where it is used to connect game characters physically to the world, such as feet landing firmly on top of terrain.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] An animated figure is modeled with a skeleton of rigid segments connected with joints, called a kinematic chain.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] The kinematics equations of the figure define the relationship between the joint angles of the figure and its pose or configuration.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] The forward kinematic animation problem uses the kinematics equations to determine the pose given the joint angles.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] The *inverse kinematics problem* computes the joint angles for a desired pose of the figure.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] It is often easier for computer-based designers, artists, and animators to define the spatial configuration of an assembly or figure by moving parts, or arms and legs, rather than directly manipulating joint angles.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] Therefore, inverse kinematics is used in computer-aided design systems to animate assemblies and by computer-based artists and animators to position figures and characters.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] The assembly is modeled as rigid links connected by joints that are defined as mates, or geometric constraints.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] Movement of one element requires the computation of the joint angles for the other elements to maintain the joint constraints.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] For example, inverse kinematics allows an artist to move the hand of a 3D human model to a desired position and orientation and have an algorithm select the proper angles of the wrist, elbow, and shoulder joints.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] Successful implementation of computer animation usually also requires that the figure move within reasonable anthropomorphic limits.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] A method of comparing both forward and inverse kinematics for the animation of a character can be defined by the advantages inherent to each.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] For instance, blocking animation where large motion arcs are used is often more advantageous in forward kinematics.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] However, more delicate animation and positioning of the target end effector in relation to other models might be easier using inverted kinematics.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] Modern digital creation packages (DCC) offer methods to apply both forward and inverse kinematics to models.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] In some, but not all cases, there exist analytical solutions to inverse kinematic problems.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] One such example is for a robot with 6 degrees of freedom (DOF) (for example, 6 revolute joints) moving in 3D space (with 3-position DOF, and 3 rotational DOF).
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] If the DOF of the robot equals or exceeds that of the end effector, for example with a 7-DoF robot with 7 revolute joints, then there exist infinitely many solutions to the IK problem and an analytical solution does not exist.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] Further extending this example, it is possible to fix one joint and analytically solve for the other joints, but a better solution is perhaps offered by numerical methods, which can instead optimize a solution given additional preferences (costs in an optimization problem).
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] An analytic solution to an inverse kinematics problem is a closed-form expression that takes the end-effector pose as input and gives joint positions as output, $q=f(x)$ .
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] Analytical inverse kinematics solvers can be significantly faster than numerical solvers and provide more than one solution, but only a finite number of solutions, for a given end-effector pose.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] Many different programs (Such as FOSS programs IKFast and Inverse Kinematics Library) are able to solve these problems quickly and efficiently using different algorithms such as the FABRIK solver.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] One issue with these solvers, is that they are known to not necessarily give locally smooth solutions between two adjacent configurations, which can cause instability if iterative solutions to inverse kinematics are required, such as if the IK is solved inside a high-rate control loop.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] Many industrial 6DOF robots feature three rotational joints with intersecting axes ("spherical wrist").
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] These robots, known as robots with an "Ortho-parallel Basis and a Spherical Wrist," can be defined by 7 kinematic parameters that are distances in their assumed standard geometry.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] These robots may have up to 8 independent solutions for any given position and rotation of the robot tool head.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] Open-source solutions for C++ and Rust exist.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] OPW has also been integrated into ROS framework.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] There are many methods of modelling and solving inverse kinematics problems.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] The most flexible of these methods typically rely on iterative optimization to seek out an approximate solution, due to the difficulty of inverting the forward kinematics equation and the possibility of an empty solution space.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] The core idea behind several of these methods is to model the forward kinematics equation using a Taylor series expansion, which can be simpler to invert and solve than the original system.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] The Jacobian inverse technique is a simple yet effective way of implementing inverse kinematics.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] Let there be m variables that govern the forward-kinematics equation, i.e. the position function.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] These variables may be joint angles, lengths, or other arbitrary real values.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] If, for example, the IK system lives in a 3-dimensional space, the position function can be viewed as a mapping $p(x):\mathbb {R} ^{m}\rightarrow \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ .
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] The Jacobian inverse technique iteratively computes an estimate of $\Delta x$ that minimizes the error given by $||p(x_{0}+\Delta x_{\text{estimate}})-p_{1}||$ .
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] where $J_{p}(x_{0})$ is the (3 × m) Jacobian matrix of the position function at $x_{0}$ .
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] where $p_{i}(x)$ gives the i-th component of the position function, $x_{0,k}+h$ is simply $x_{0}$ with a small delta added to its k-th component, and h is a reasonably small positive value.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] Applying the inverse Jacobian method once will result in a very rough estimate of the desired $\Delta x$ -vector.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] A line search should be used to scale this $\Delta x$ to an acceptable value.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] Once some $\Delta x$ -vector has caused the error to drop close to zero, the algorithm should terminate.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] Existing methods based on the Hessian matrix of the system have been reported to converge to desired $\Delta x$ values using fewer iterations, though, in some cases more computational resources.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] The inverse kinematics problem can also be approximated using heuristic methods.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] These methods perform simple, iterative operations to gradually lead to an approximation of the solution.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] The heuristic algorithms have low computational cost (return the final pose very quickly), and usually support joint constraints.
[src:ragdoll-physics/inverse-kinematics] The most popular heuristic algorithms are cyclic coordinate descent (CCD) and forward and backward reaching inverse kinematics (FABRIK).
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] A **physics engine** is computer software that provides an approximate simulation of certain physical systems, typically classical dynamics, including rigid body dynamics (including collision detection), soft body dynamics, and fluid dynamics.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] It is of use in the domains of computer graphics, video games and film (CGI).
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Their main uses are in video games (typically as middleware), in which case the simulations are in real-time.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] The term is sometimes used more generally to describe any software system for simulating physical phenomena, such as high-performance scientific simulation.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] There are generally two classes of physics engines: real-time and high-precision.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] High-precision physics engines require more processing power to calculate very precise physics and are usually used by scientists and prerendered computer animation, such as movies.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Real-time physics engines—as used in video games and other forms of interactive computing—use simplified calculations and decreased accuracy to compute in time for the game to respond at an appropriate rate for game play.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] A physics engine is essentially a big calculator that does mathematics needed to simulate physics.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] One of the first general purpose computers, ENIAC, was used as a very simple type of physics engine.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] It was used to design ballistics tables to help the United States military estimate where artillery shells of various mass would land when fired at varying angles and gunpowder charges, also accounting for drift caused by wind.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] The results were calculated a single time only, and were tabulated into printed tables handed out to the artillery commanders.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Physics engines have been commonly used on supercomputers since the 1980s to perform computational fluid dynamics modeling, where particles are assigned force vectors that are combined to show circulation.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Due to the requirements of speed and high precision, special computer processors known as vector processors were developed to accelerate the calculations.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] The techniques can be used to model weather patterns in weather forecasting, wind tunnel data for designing air- and watercraft or motor vehicles including racecars, and thermal cooling of computer processors for improving heat sinks.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] As with many calculation-laden processes in computing, the accuracy of the simulation is related to the resolution of the simulation and the precision of the calculations; small fluctuations not modeled in the simulation can drastically change the predicted results.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Tire manufacturers use physics simulations to examine how new tire tread types will perform under wet and dry conditions, using new tire materials of varying flexibility and under different levels of weight loading.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] The simulations optimize tire operations, material selection, costs, and enhance time efficiency.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] In most computer games, speed of the processors and gameplay are more important than accuracy of simulation.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] This leads to designs for physics engines that produce results in real-time but that replicate real world physics only for simple cases and typically with some approximation.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] More often than not, the simulation is geared towards providing a "perceptually correct" approximation rather than a real simulation.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] However some game engines, such as Source, use physics in puzzles or in combat situations.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] This requires more accurate physics so that, for example, the momentum of an object can knock over an obstacle or lift a sinking object.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Physically-based character animation in the past only used rigid body dynamics because they are faster and easier to calculate, but modern games and movies are starting to use soft body physics.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Soft body physics are also used for particle effects, liquids and cloth.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Some form of limited fluid dynamics simulation is sometimes provided to simulate water and other liquids as well as the flow of fire and explosions through the air.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Objects in games interact with the player, the environment, and each other.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Typically, most 3D objects in games are represented by two separate meshes or shapes.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] One of these meshes is the highly complex and detailed shape visible to the player in the game, such as a vase with elegant curved and looping handles.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] For purpose of speed, a second, simplified invisible mesh is used to represent the object to the physics engine so that the physics engine treats the example vase as a simple cylinder.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] It would thus be impossible to insert a rod or fire a projectile through the handle holes on the vase, because the physics engine model is based on the cylinder and is unaware of the handles.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] The simplified mesh used for physics processing is often referred to as the collision geometry.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] This may be a bounding box, sphere, or convex hull.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Engines that use bounding boxes or bounding spheres as the final shape for collision detection are considered extremely simple.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Generally a bounding box is used for broad phase collision detection to narrow down the number of possible collisions before costly mesh on mesh collision detection is done in the narrow phase of collision detection.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Another aspect of precision in discrete collision detection involves the framerate, or the number of moments in time per second when physics is calculated.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Each frame is treated as separate from all other frames, and the space between frames is not calculated.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] A low framerate and a small fast-moving object causes a situation where the object does not move smoothly through space but instead seems to teleport from one point in space to the next as each frame is calculated.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Projectiles moving at sufficiently high speeds will miss targets, if the target is small enough to fit in the gap between the calculated frames of the fast moving projectile.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Various techniques are used to overcome this flaw, such as *Second Life*'s representation of projectiles as arrows with invisible trailing tails longer than the gap in frames to collide with any object that might fit between the calculated frames.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] By contrast, continuous collision detection such as in Bullet or Havok does not suffer this problem.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] An alternative to using bounding box-based rigid body physics systems is to use a finite element-based system.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] In such a system, a 3-dimensional, volumetric tessellation is created of the 3D object.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] The tessellation results in a number of finite elements which represent aspects of the object's physical properties such as toughness, plasticity, and volume preservation.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Once constructed, the finite elements are used by a solver to model the stress within the 3D object.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] The stress can be used to drive fracture, deformation and other physical effects with a high degree of realism and uniqueness.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] As the number of modeled elements is increased, the engine's ability to model physical behavior increases.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] The visual representation of the 3D object is altered by the finite element system through the use of a deformation shader run on the CPU or GPU.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Finite Element-based systems had been impractical for use in games due to the performance overhead and the lack of tools to create finite element representations out of 3D art objects.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] James O'Brien as a part of his PhD thesis.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] In the real world, physics is always active.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] There is a constant Brownian motion jitter to all particles in our universe as the forces push back and forth against each other.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] For a game physics engine, such constant active precision is unnecessarily wasting the limited CPU power, which can cause problems such as decreased framerate.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Thus, games may put objects to "sleep" by disabling the computation of physics on objects that have not moved a particular distance within a certain amount of time.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] For example, in the 3D virtual world Second Life, if an object is resting on the floor and the object does not move beyond a minimal distance in about two seconds, then the physics calculations are disabled for the object and it becomes frozen in place.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] The object remains frozen until physics processing reactivates for the object after collision occurs with some other active physical object.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Physics engines for video games typically have two core components, a collision detection/collision response system, and the dynamics simulation component responsible for solving the forces affecting the simulated objects.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Modern physics engines may also contain fluid simulations, animation control systems and asset integration tools.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Finally, hybrid methods are possible that combine aspects of the above paradigms.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] A primary limit of physics engine realism is the approximated result of the constraint resolutions and collision result due to the slow convergence of algorithms.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Collision detection computed at a too low frequency can result in objects passing through each other and then being repelled with an abnormal correction force.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] On the other hand, approximated results of reaction force is due to the slow convergence of typical Projected Gauss Seidel solver resulting in abnormal bouncing.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Any type of free-moving compound physics object can demonstrate this problem, but it is especially prone to affecting chain links under high tension, and wheeled objects with actively physical bearing surfaces.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Higher precision reduces the positional/force errors, but at the cost of needing greater CPU power for the calculations.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] A physics processing unit (PPU) is a dedicated microprocessor designed to handle the calculations of physics, especially in the physics engine of video games.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Examples of calculations involving a PPU might include rigid body dynamics, soft body dynamics, collision detection, fluid dynamics, hair and clothing simulation, finite element analysis, and fracturing of objects.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] The idea is that specialized processors offload time-consuming tasks from a computer's CPU, much like how a GPU performs graphics operations in the main CPU's place.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] The term was coined by Ageia's marketing to describe their PhysX chip to consumers.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Several other technologies in the CPU-GPU spectrum have some features in common with it, although Ageia's solution was the only complete one designed, marketed, supported, and placed within a system *exclusively* as a PPU.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] Hardware acceleration for physics processing is now usually provided by graphics processing units that support more general computation, a concept known as general-purpose computing on graphics processing units (GPGPU).
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] AMD and NVIDIA provide support for rigid body dynamics computations on their latest graphics cards.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] NVIDIA's GeForce 8 series supports a GPU-based Newtonian physics acceleration technology named *Quantum Effects Technology*.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] NVIDIA provides an SDK Toolkit for CUDA (Compute Unified Device Architecture) technology that offers both a low and high-level API to the GPU.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] For their GPUs, AMD offers a similar SDK, called Close to Metal (CTM), which provides a thin hardware interface.
[src:ragdoll-physics/physics-engine] PhysX is an example of a physics engine that can use GPGPU based hardware acceleration when it is available.
[src:ragdoll-physics/ragdoll-physics] Early video games used manually created animations for a character’s death sequences.
[src:ragdoll-physics/ragdoll-physics] This had the advantage of low CPU utilization, as the data needed to animate a "dying" character was chosen from a set number of pre-drawn frames.
[src:ragdoll-physics/ragdoll-physics] In contrast, a ragdoll is a collection of multiple rigid bodies (each of which is ordinarily tied to a bone in the graphics engine's skeletal animation system) tied together by a system of constraints that restrict how the bones may move relative to each other.
[src:ragdoll-physics/ragdoll-physics] When the character dies, their body begins to collapse to the ground, honouring these restrictions on each of the joints' motion, which often looks more realistic.
[src:ragdoll-physics/ragdoll-physics] The term *ragdoll* comes from the problem that the articulated systems, due to the limits of the solvers used, tend to have little or zero joint/skeletal muscle stiffness, leading to a character collapsing much like a toy rag doll, often into comically improbable or compromising positions.
[src:ragdoll-physics/ragdoll-physics] Modern use of ragdoll physics goes beyond death sequences.
[src:ragdoll-physics/ragdoll-physics] The *Jurassic Park* licensed game *Jurassic Park: Trespasser* exhibited ragdoll physics in 1998 but received very polarised opinions; most were negative, as the game had a large number of bugs.
[src:ragdoll-physics/ragdoll-physics] It was remembered, however, for being a pioneer in video game physics.
[src:ragdoll-physics/ragdoll-physics] There are fighting games where the player controls one part of the body of the fighter and the rest follows along, such as *Rag Doll Kung Fu*, as well as racing games such as the *FlatOut* series.
[src:ragdoll-physics/ragdoll-physics] Ragdolls have been implemented using Featherstone's algorithm and spring-damper contacts.
[src:ragdoll-physics/ragdoll-physics] An alternative approach uses constraint solvers and idealized contacts.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] In classical mechanics, **rigid body dynamics** studies the movement of systems of interconnected bodies under the action of external forces.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Along with statics, it forms the field of **rigid body mechanics**.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The assumption that the bodies are *rigid* (i.e. they do not deform under the action of applied forces) simplifies analysis, by reducing the parameters that describe the configuration of the system to the translation and rotation of body-fixed frames.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] This excludes bodies that display fluid, highly elastic, and plastic behavior.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The dynamics of a rigid body system is described by the laws of kinematics and by the application of Newton's second law (kinetics) or their derivative form, Lagrangian mechanics.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The solution of these equations of motion provides a description of the position, the motion and the acceleration of the individual components of the system, and overall the system itself, as a function of time.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The formulation and solution of rigid body dynamics is an important tool in the computer simulation of mechanical systems.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] If a system of particles moves parallel to a fixed plane, the system is said to be constrained to planar movement.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] In this case, Newton's laws (kinetics) for a rigid system of N particles, P*i*, *i*=1,...,*N*, simplify because there is no movement in the *k* direction.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] where **r**i denotes the planar trajectory of each particle.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] For systems that are constrained to planar movement, the angular velocity and angular acceleration vectors are directed along **k** perpendicular to the plane of movement, which simplifies this acceleration equation.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] where ${\textstyle \mathbf {e} _{i}\times \mathbf {e} _{i}=0}$ and ${\textstyle \mathbf {e} _{i}\times \mathbf {t} _{i}=\mathbf {k} }$ is the unit vector perpendicular to the plane for all of the particles Pi.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] where M is the total mass and *I***C** is the moment of inertia about an axis perpendicular to the movement of the rigid system and through the center of mass.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Several methods to describe orientations of a rigid body in three dimensions have been developed.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] They are summarized in the following sections.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The first attempt to represent an orientation is attributed to Leonhard Euler.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The values of these three rotations are called Euler angles.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Commonly, $\psi$ is used to denote precession, $\theta$ nutation, and $\phi$ intrinsic rotation.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] These are three angles, also known as yaw, pitch and roll, Navigation angles and Cardan angles.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Mathematically they constitute a set of six possibilities inside the twelve possible sets of Euler angles, the ordering being the one best used for describing the orientation of a vehicle such as an airplane.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] In aerospace engineering they are usually referred to as Euler angles.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Euler also realized that the composition of two rotations is equivalent to a single rotation about a different fixed axis (Euler's rotation theorem).
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Therefore, the composition of the former three angles has to be equal to only one rotation, whose axis was complicated to calculate until matrices were developed.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Based on this fact he introduced a vectorial way to describe any rotation, with a vector on the rotation axis and module equal to the value of the angle.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Therefore, any orientation can be represented by a rotation vector (also called Euler vector) that leads to it from the reference frame.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] When used to represent an orientation, the rotation vector is commonly called orientation vector, or attitude vector.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] A similar method, called axis-angle representation, describes a rotation or orientation using a unit vector aligned with the rotation axis, and a separate value to indicate the angle (see figure).
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] With the introduction of matrices the Euler theorems were rewritten.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The rotations were described by orthogonal matrices referred to as rotation matrices or direction cosine matrices.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] When used to represent an orientation, a rotation matrix is commonly called orientation matrix, or attitude matrix.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The above-mentioned Euler vector is the eigenvector of a rotation matrix (a rotation matrix has a unique real eigenvalue).
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The product of two rotation matrices is the composition of rotations.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Therefore, as before, the orientation can be given as the rotation from the initial frame to achieve the frame that we want to describe.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The configuration space of a non-symmetrical object in *n*-dimensional space is SO(*n*) × **R***n*.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Orientation may be visualized by attaching a basis of tangent vectors to an object.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The direction in which each vector points determines its orientation.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Another way to describe rotations is using rotation quaternions, also called versors.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] They are equivalent to rotation matrices and rotation vectors.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] With respect to rotation vectors, they can be more easily converted to and from matrices.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] When used to represent orientations, rotation quaternions are typically called orientation quaternions or attitude quaternions.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] To consider rigid body dynamics in three-dimensional space, Newton's second law must be extended to define the relationship between the movement of a rigid body and the system of forces and torques that act on it.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The extension of Newton's second law to rigid bodies is achieved by considering a rigid system of particles.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] If a system of *N* particles, Pi, i=1,...,*N*, are assembled into a rigid body, then Newton's second law can be applied to each of the particles in the body.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] An important simplification to these force equations is obtained by introducing the resultant force and torque that acts on the rigid system.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] This resultant force and torque is obtained by choosing one of the particles in the system as a reference point, **R**, where each of the external forces are applied with the addition of an associated torque.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The resultant force **F** and torque **T** are given by the formulas, $\mathbf {F} =\sum _{i=1}^{N}\mathbf {F} _{i},\quad \mathbf {T} =\sum _{i=1}^{N}(\mathbf {R} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )\times \mathbf {F} _{i},$ where **R**i is the vector that defines the position of particle Pi.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The mass properties of the rigid body are represented by its center of mass and inertia matrix.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] then it is known as the center of mass of the system.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] where $\mathbf {S} _{i}$ is the column vector **R**i − **R**; $\mathbf {S} _{i}^{\textsf {T}}$ is its transpose, and $\mathbf {I}$ is the 3 by 3 identity matrix.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] $\mathbf {S} _{i}^{\textsf {T}}\mathbf {S} _{i}$ is the scalar product of $\mathbf {S} _{i}$ with itself, while $\mathbf {S} _{i}\mathbf {S} _{i}^{\textsf {T}}$ is the tensor product of $\mathbf {S} _{i}$ with itself.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Using the center of mass and inertia matrix, the force and torque equations for a single rigid body take the form $\mathbf {F} =m\mathbf {a} ,\quad \mathbf {T} =[I_{R}]\alpha +\omega \times [I_{R}]\omega ,$ and are known as Newton's second law of motion for a rigid body.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The dynamics of an interconnected system of rigid bodies, *B**i*, *j* = 1, ..., *M*, is formulated by isolating each rigid body and introducing the interaction forces.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Newton's formulation yields 6*M* equations that define the dynamics of a system of *M* rigid bodies.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] A rotating object, whether under the influence of torques or not, may exhibit the behaviours of precession and nutation.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The solution to this equation when there is no applied torque is discussed in the articles Euler's equation of motion and Poinsot's ellipsoid.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] It follows from Euler's equation that a torque **τ** applied perpendicular to the axis of rotation, and therefore perpendicular to **L**, results in a rotation about an axis perpendicular to both **τ** and **L**.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Precession can be demonstrated by placing a spinning top with its axis horizontal and supported loosely (frictionless toward precession) at one end.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Instead of falling, as might be expected, the top appears to defy gravity by remaining with its axis horizontal, when the other end of the axis is left unsupported and the free end of the axis slowly describes a circle in a horizontal plane, the resulting precession turning.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] This effect is explained by the above equations.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The torque on the top is supplied by a couple of forces: gravity acting downward on the device's centre of mass, and an equal force acting upward to support one end of the device.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Under a constant torque of magnitude *τ*, the speed of precession *Ω*P is inversely proportional to *L*, the magnitude of its angular momentum: $\tau ={\mathit {\Omega }}_{\mathrm {P} }L\sin \theta ,$ where *θ* is the angle between the vectors **Ω**P and **L**.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Thus, if the top's spin slows down (for example, due to friction), its angular momentum decreases and so the rate of precession increases.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] This continues until the device is unable to rotate fast enough to support its own weight, when it stops precessing and falls off its support, mostly because friction against precession cause another precession that goes to cause the fall.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] By convention, these three vectors – torque, spin, and precession – are all oriented with respect to each other according to the right-hand rule.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] An alternate formulation of rigid body dynamics that has a number of convenient features is obtained by considering the virtual work of forces acting on a rigid body.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The virtual work of forces acting at various points on a single rigid body can be calculated using the velocities of their point of application and the resultant force and torque.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The trajectories of **R***i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n* are defined by the movement of the rigid body.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The velocity of the points **R***i* along their trajectories are $\mathbf {V} _{i}={\boldsymbol {\omega }}\times (\mathbf {R} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )+\mathbf {V} ,$ where **ω** is the angular velocity vector of the body.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] is known as the generalized force associated with the virtual displacement δq.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] It is useful to note that conservative forces such as gravity and spring forces are derivable from a potential function *V*(*q*1, ..., *q**n*), known as a potential energy.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The equations of motion for a mechanical system of rigid bodies can be determined using D'Alembert's form of the principle of virtual work.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The principle of virtual work is used to study the static equilibrium of a system of rigid bodies; however, by introducing acceleration terms in Newton's laws this approach is generalized to define dynamic equilibrium.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The static equilibrium of a mechanical system rigid bodies is defined by the condition that the virtual work of the applied forces is zero for any virtual displacement of the system.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] This is known as the *principle of virtual work.* This is equivalent to the requirement that the generalized forces for any virtual displacement are zero, that is *Q**i*=0.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Let a mechanical system be constructed from n rigid bodies, B*i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n*, and let the resultant of the applied forces on each body be the force-torque pairs, **F***i* and **T***i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n*.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Notice that these applied forces do not include the reaction forces where the bodies are connected.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Finally, assume that the velocity **V***i* and angular velocities ***ω****i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n*, for each rigid body, are defined by a single generalized coordinate q.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Such a system of rigid bodies is said to have one degree of freedom.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] These m equations define the static equilibrium of the system of rigid bodies.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Consider a single rigid body which moves under the action of a resultant force **F** and torque **T**, with one degree of freedom defined by the generalized coordinate *q*.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] D'Alembert's form of the principle of virtual work states that a system of rigid bodies is in dynamic equilibrium when the virtual work of the sum of the applied forces and the inertial forces is zero for any virtual displacement of the system.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Thus, dynamic equilibrium of a system of n rigid bodies with m generalized coordinates requires that $\delta W=\left(Q_{1}+Q_{1}^{*}\right)\delta q_{1}+\dots +\left(Q_{m}+Q_{m}^{*}\right)\delta q_{m}=0,$ for any set of virtual displacements *δq**j*.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] In this case, introduce the Lagrangian, *L* = *T* − *V*, so these equations of motion become ${\frac {d}{dt}}{\frac {\partial L}{\partial {\dot {q}}_{j}}}-{\frac {\partial L}{\partial q_{j}}}=0\quad j=1,\ldots ,m.$ These are known as Lagrange's equations of motion.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The linear and angular momentum of a rigid system of particles is formulated by measuring the position and velocity of the particles relative to the center of mass.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Let the system of particles Pi, *i* = 1, ..., *n* be located at the coordinates **r***i* and velocities **v***i*.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] To specialize these formulas to a rigid body, assume the particles are rigidly connected to each other so Pi, i=1,...,n are located by the coordinates **r**i and velocities **v**i.
[src:ragdoll-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Select a reference point **R** and compute the relative position and velocity vectors, $\mathbf {r} _{i}=(\mathbf {r} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )+\mathbf {R} ,\quad \mathbf {v} _{i}=\omega \times (\mathbf {r} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )+\mathbf {V} ,$ where ω is the angular velocity of the system.
[src:ragdoll-physics/skeletal-animation] The technique was introduced in 1988 by Nadia Magnenat Thalmann, Richard Laperrière, and Daniel Thalmann.
[src:ragdoll-physics/skeletal-animation] This technique is used in virtually all animation systems where simplified user interfaces allow animators to control often complex algorithms and a huge amount of geometry; most notably through inverse kinematics and other "goal-oriented" techniques.
[src:ragdoll-physics/skeletal-animation] This technique constructs a series of bones (which need not correspond to any real-world anatomical feature), sometimes also referred to as rigging in the noun sense.
[src:ragdoll-physics/skeletal-animation] Each bone has a three-dimensional transformation from the default bind pose (which includes its position, scale and orientation), and an optional parent bone.
[src:ragdoll-physics/skeletal-animation] The full transform of a child node is the product of its parent transform and its own transform.
[src:ragdoll-physics/skeletal-animation] So moving a thigh-bone will move the lower leg too.
[src:ragdoll-physics/skeletal-animation] As the character is animated, the bones change their transformation over time, under the influence of some animation controller.
[src:ragdoll-physics/skeletal-animation] A rig is generally composed of both forward kinematics and inverse kinematics parts that may interact with each other.
[src:ragdoll-physics/skeletal-animation] Skeletal animation is referring to the forward kinematics part of the rig, where a complete set of bone configurations identifies a unique pose.
[src:ragdoll-physics/skeletal-animation] Each bone in the skeleton is associated with some portion of the character's visual representation (the mesh) in a process called skinning.
[src:ragdoll-physics/skeletal-animation] In the most common case of a polygonal mesh character, the bone is associated with a group of vertices; for example, in a model of a human being, the bone for the thigh would be associated with the vertices making up the polygons in the model's thigh.
[src:ragdoll-physics/skeletal-animation] Portions of the character's skin can normally be associated with multiple bones, each one having a scaling factor called vertex weights, or blend weights.
[src:ragdoll-physics/skeletal-animation] The movement of skin near the joints of two bones, can therefore be influenced by both bones.
[src:ragdoll-physics/skeletal-animation] In most state-of-the-art graphical engines, the skinning process is done on the GPU by a shader program.
[src:ragdoll-physics/skeletal-animation] For a polygonal mesh, each vertex can have a blend weight for each bone.
[src:ragdoll-physics/skeletal-animation] To calculate the final position of the vertex, a transformation matrix is created for each bone which, when applied to the vertex, first puts the vertex in bone space then puts it back into mesh space.
[src:ragdoll-physics/skeletal-animation] After applying a matrix to the vertex, it is scaled by its corresponding weight.
[src:ragdoll-physics/skeletal-animation] This algorithm is called matrix-palette skinning or linear-blend skinning, because the set of bone transformations (stored as transform matrices) form a palette for the skin vertex to choose from.
[src:ragdoll-physics/skeletal-animation] Skeletal animation is the standard way to animate characters or mechanical objects for a prolonged period of time.
[src:ragdoll-physics/skeletal-animation] It is commonly used by video game artists and in the film industry, and can also be applied to mechanical objects and any other objects made up of rigid elements and joints.
[src:ragdoll-physics/skeletal-animation] Performance capture (or motion capture) can speed up the process of skeletal animation, as well as increasing the level of realism.
[src:ragdoll-physics/skeletal-animation] Rigs may be driven by ragdoll physics which automatically calculate physics of motion and resistance with skeletal frames.
[src:ragdoll-physics/skeletal-animation] Virtual anatomy properties such as weight of limbs, muscle reaction, bone strength, and joint constraints may be added for realistic bouncing, buckling, fracture, and tumbling effects.
[src:ragdoll-physics/skeletal-animation] Some popular software packages within which rigs may be created include Blender, Autodesk Maya, SideFX Houdini, Autodesk 3ds Max, Maxon Cinema 4D, Unreal Engine, and many others.
